&lt;p&gt;The Correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Equal pay for equal work&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;color: (33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Article 39&lt;/strong&gt; of the Indian Constitution is a part of the &lt;strong&gt;Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP)&lt;/strong&gt;, which aims to establish social and economic democracy in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This article directs the State to ensure that there is &lt;strong&gt;equal pay for equal work&lt;/strong&gt; for both men and women.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It reflects the principle of &lt;strong&gt;gender equality&lt;/strong&gt; and seeks to remove discrimination based on gender in employment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The provision is aimed at promoting &lt;strong&gt;social justice&lt;/strong&gt; and ensuring fairness in the workplace.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Although the Directive Principles are not legally enforceable, they provide a &lt;strong&gt;guiding framework&lt;/strong&gt; for the State to formulate laws and policies.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The concept of &lt;strong&gt;equal pay for equal work&lt;/strong&gt; has been upheld and reinforced by the judiciary in various landmark judgments, including by the &lt;strong&gt;Supreme Court of India&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The principle is crucial for reducing &lt;strong&gt;wage disparity&lt;/strong&gt; and fostering equality in labor practices across various sectors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Right to privacy&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Right to Privacy&lt;/strong&gt; is not explicitly mentioned in the Directive Principles but has been interpreted as a fundamental right under &lt;strong&gt;Article 21&lt;/strong&gt; of the Constitution by the Supreme Court.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It ensures protection from arbitrary interference in a person&amp;rsquo;s private life by the State or others.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The landmark &lt;strong&gt;Puttaswamy judgment (2017)&lt;/strong&gt; established the Right to Privacy as a fundamental right in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;State to secure a social order&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This is addressed under &lt;strong&gt;Article 38&lt;/strong&gt; of the Constitution, which directs the State to strive to promote the welfare of the people by securing a social order based on &lt;strong&gt;justice, social, economic, and political&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It complements Article 39 by laying down broader objectives to ensure equitable distribution of resources and opportunities.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Right to work&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Right to Work&lt;/strong&gt; is addressed under &lt;strong&gt;Article 41&lt;/strong&gt; of the Directive Principles, which directs the State to provide work, education, and public assistance in cases of unemployment, old age, sickness, and other areas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act (MGNREGA)&lt;/strong&gt; is a key example of efforts to implement this principle.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Census Act 1948&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Census Act 1948 provides the legal framework for conducting the decennial Census in India.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It was enacted by the Parliament of India to ensure the systematic collection of demographic data.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The act empowers the government to conduct the census and collect demographic information such as population size, growth, density, and other vital statistics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Census of India is conducted every 10 years, and it is one of the most extensive administrative exercises in the country.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Decennial Census:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The decennial census is a comprehensive exercise conducted every ten years to gather demographic data about the population of a country.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It includes data on population size, density, growth rate, age distribution, sex ratio, literacy rate, and other socio-economic factors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This data is crucial for planning and policy-making by the government.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Census Act 1948:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Census Act 1948 was enacted to provide the legal foundation for conducting the census in India.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The act outlines the duties and responsibilities of census officers and the procedures for data collection and confidentiality.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It ensures that the data collected during the census is used solely for statistical purposes and is kept confidential.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Importance of Census:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The census data is vital for the government to allocate resources, plan infrastructure, and implement various welfare schemes effectively.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps in identifying demographic trends and making informed decisions for the socio-economic development of the country.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The data is used for electoral constituency delimitation, urban planning, and understanding population dynamics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kerala&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kerala&lt;/strong&gt; is the&lt;strong&gt; largest producer of rubber plantation&lt;/strong&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;India&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
